TableContextTimeStampAfterTable: {20198=2014 First player in program history to be named an NEIBA, D3Baseball.com, ECAC New England All-Region selection … Earned third team honors from the NEIBA and first team honors from D3Baseball.com and the ECAC … Named the Little East Conference Co-Offensive Player of the Year and First Team selection … Became just the second player in school history to be selected in the MLB Amateur Draft as he was chosen in the 32nd round and was the 961st pick overall … Hit a team-leading .333 on the year and had a .497 on-base and .563 slugging percentage … Totaled 45 hits, 29 RBI, and 38 runs scored in 135 at-bats … Started in all 41 games for the Beacons … Recorded seven doubles, three triples, and four home runs … His 41 walks led all Division III baseball, while his 19 stolen bases led the Beacons roster … Currently sits in the top-10 in multiple categories in program history including at-bats with 416, hits with 143, career batting average with .344, doubles with 27, triples with 11, home runs with 12, total bases with 228, slugging percentage with .548, and walks with 85 … Tied the program record for triples in a season with six and triples in a game with two … Had his best offensive day when he went 3-for-6 with a double and two triples and had five RBI and two runs scored in the April 3 win at Westfield State University … Went 3-for-4 with two runs scored and two RBI against Framingham State University on April 9 … Crushed his first home run of the year against the University of Dubuque on March 21 … Was walked a season-high three times on March 20 against Bethel University and on April 6 against Western Connecticut State University., 25241=PERSONAL/HIGH SCHOOL Graduated from Madison Park Technical Vocational High School in Roxbury, Mass. in 2010 ... Member of his high school's baseball and basketball teams ... Named Division II Player of the Year for baseball ... Three-time League All-Star ... All-Scholastic honoree as a senior ... Earned four varsity letters with the baseball team ... Named team captain three-times ... Helped the baseball team to back-to-back league championships ... Won the Division I South Sectional State Championship with the basketball team ... Named Male Athlete of the Year at his high school as a senior ... Born on February 13, 1992 ... Son of Nadira Seguie ... Was walked a team-best 24 times, and also led the Beacons with 20 stolen bases … As the Beacons starting outfielder he combined for 85 putouts and six assists … Started in 37 of the 39 games played in his junior season … Recorded a season high four hits in five at-bats and accounted for two runs in the non-conference win over Framingham State University on April 18 … Had his best day of the year when he went 3-for-6 with five RBI and two runs scored in game one of the doubleheader with Western Connecticut State University on May 3 … Recorded a hit streak of six straight games with two or more hits … Went 3-for-4 with four RBI and two runs scored in the opener against LEC opponent UMass Dartmouth on March 30 … Posted a season-high three stolen bases and three walks at Bridgewater State University on April 9 … Went 3-for-5 with three runs scored and one run batted in against Keene State College on May 8 in the first round of the Little East Conference tournament.}
